[5] Australia (Queensland)
Date: Mon 1 Dec 2008
Source: ABC News (Australian Broadcasting Corporation) [edited]
<http://www.abc.net.au/news/stories/2008/12/01/2434429.htm>


Health authorities expect there will be more cases of dengue fever in
Cairns, in far north Queensland, after 2 people were diagnosed with
the mosquito-borne disease [virus].

An outbreak has been declared, with the Tropical Population Health
Service also investigating another 5 suspected cases.

Medical entomologist Dr Scott Ritchie says the infections are centred
in the Cairns north area.

"The worrisome thing about this is it's in an area of older housing
and with the rains that we've had in the last fortnight, we suspect
there's a fair amount of mosquito breeding going on in the area," he
said.

It is 4 years since the last outbreak of dengue fever in Cairns, when
29 people fell ill.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[Cairns in northern Queensland can be located on the map at
<http://www.lib.utexas.edu/maps/australia/australia_pol99.jpg> and
the HealthMap/ProMED-mail interactive map of Australia at
