[6] St Kits
Date: Thu 27 Nov 2008
Source: SKNVibes [edited]
<http://www.sknvibes.com/News/NewsDetails.cfm/7548>


Weeks of speculation on the existence of dengue fever in the
Federation were affirmed yesterday evening (26 Nov 2008) when the
Ministry of Health stated in a press release that over 2-dozen cases
of the disease have been found.

According to the release, "a number of tests were sent to the
Caribbean Epidemiology Center (CAREC) lab for confirmation" by the
Ministry of Health, and those tests have finally returned with a
positive result.

Rumours of residents suffering from the symptoms of dengue fever were
first addressed by the Ministry of Health on 23 Sep [2008] after an
upsurge in the number of reported cases in Trinidad and Guyana.

That advisory stated that there were "no reported cases of dengue in
St. Kitts and Nevis [but] since the Federation is in relatively
proximity to affected areas, prevention and surveillance efforts must
be given the highest priority."

Anecdotal reports of the disease then spread like wildfire shortly
after the torrential rainfall of Hurricane Omar created numerous
pools of standing water in St. Kitts-Nevis -- a major breeding ground
for dengue fever's [virus] top carrier, mosquitoes.

The Ministry of Health attempted to allay fears of the disease with a
1 Nov [2008] release, which stated that there still had been no
confirmed cases, but it did go on to note that a "number of persons
[were] presenting to medical practitioners with fever, pain, and
other symptoms and signs suggesting dengue virus infection."

The final confirmation of dengue fever after the CAREC tests means
that "the mosquito that spreads dengue viruses remains highly active"
in the Federation, the Ministry's release said.

It was further stated that individuals should make it their top
priority to "eradicate" mosquito breeding grounds on and around their
property by draining any standing water and contacting the
Environmental Health Department through their local health center if
assistance is required.

[Byline: Ryan Haas]

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[Health authorities are to be commended for their vigilance and
preparations for the arrival of dengue virus on St. Kits. One hopes
that their efforts to reduce vector mosquito breeding sites are
successful.

Maps showing the location of St. Kits Island in the Caribbean can be
accessed at
<http://www.ehi.com/travel/carib/kittsnevis/redmap.html>
and the HealthMap/ProMED-mail interactive map at
<http://healthmap.org/promed/en?g=3575174&v=17.333,-62.75,6>. - Mod.TY]

******
[7] Dominican Republic
Date: Thu 27 Nov 2008
Source: La Nacion Dominicana.com [in Spanish, trans. & summ. Mod.TY, edited]
<http://www.lanaciondominicana.com/ver_noticia.php?id_noticia=3984&sesion_periodico=24>


The president of the College of Physicians, Dr Waldo Ariel Suero,
issued an alert notice to the responsible authorities in reaction to
so many cases of dengue, leptospirosis, and rabies, which he said
were currently registered in public and private [health] centers in
the country.

According to Suero, the numbers of registered deaths and cases of
dengue fever are worrisome.

Public Health said that to date [27 Nov 2008] there are 3623
registered dengue cases and 30 people have died, which signifies that
there is one death for every 120 cases of the disease, while last
year [2007] there was one death per 222 [cases].

[In response, 2 physicians said] "We need an explanation because if
in 2007 to epidemiological week 48, there were 9101 cases and 41
died, that is one [death] for every 222 cases, then why now with only
3623 cases there have been 30 deaths, that is double [the case
fatality rate], one for every 120 ill people," they added.

Dengue is reported from various sectors of the capital city (Santo Domingo).

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-ESP
<promed@promedmail.org>

[There is no obvious explanation for the highly statistically
different case fatality rates with 2008 higher than in 2007. Three
possibilities are: (1) differences in reporting, with non-fatal cases
in 2008 being underreported; (2) the dengue virus strains circulating
in 2008 being more virulent than those in 2007; or (3) a dengue virus
serotype is circulating in 2008 and is different from that being
transmitted in 2007 and before, with immune enhancement of infection
in patients infected in previous years.

However, an article in Prensa Latina of 30 Nov 2008
(<http://www.plenglish.com/article.asp?ID=%7BA25622D2-0242-4DE5-B78D-E20A0F97AB2A%7D)&language=EN>)
indicated that there has been an increase to nearly 5000 dengue cases
and nearly 100 dengue-related deaths, which raises questions about
the reliability of the 2008 case fatality rates reported above. The
source of the case statistics reported in Prensa Latina was
attributed to "epidemiological sources," without specifying who or
what those sources might be, or how many of these cases had been
laboratory confirmed. The article stated that fumigation for vector
control had begun.

ProMED-mail would appreciate receiving any additional information
about this dengue outbreak. A comparative genetic analysis of the
dengue viruses being transmitted in 2007 and 2008 would be
interesting.

A map of the Dominican Republic showing the location of Santo Domingo
can be accessed at
<http://www.lib.utexas.edu/maps/americas/dominican_republic_pol_04.jpg>
A HealthMap/ProMED-mail interactive map of the Dominican Republic can
be accessed at
<http://healthmap.org/promed/en?v=18.9,-70.5,5>. - Mod.TY]
